Advantages and Disadvantages of Converting Credits to Swiss Francs
On the banking market there have already appeared two offers of conversion in lei of credits in Swiss francs, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come in a few years, when the variable interest rate can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process of converting credits into francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost has announced the conversion offer for its customers.
According to data accumulated by analysts of financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest at lei, of 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, the Transylvania Bank’s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of customers with credits in francs due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced with the amount of risk and management fees paid by the customer, then an additional 22.5% reduction was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to the equivalent monthly plateau in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the next years.
Benefits
The main advantage of the loan cover in CHF is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future increases of the franc, and the repayment of the credit will be made in the currency in which he collects his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that no reassessment of ownership, no further guarantees and another proof of income are required.
Practically, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the loan, nor will there be additional costs as in the case of a refinancing firm.
Also, both banks offer a discount at the monthly rate, compared to how much plateau customers before conversion, equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the early years is made up more of the interest rate, and the customer pays back very little of the principal.
The Bancpost offer with very low interest rates in the first three years seems advantageous for customers.
It is not known how this rate will change after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be more than 3.25%, so in total, and the cost reduction is lower.
A possible risk for all loans in lei with variable interest rates is that the ROBOR index will increase significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor index - CHF).
