Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, artists and not commercial representatives.
The French violinist David Grimal is one of the great artists of our time, known not only as a soloist but also as the initiator of a less common project, rightly "weird", as he says, Les Dissonances - an orchestra made up of international soloists and talented musicians, who perform a symphonic repertoire without having a conductor.
Les Dissonances was this year at the Enescu Festival with two performances: a performance, on Sunday, in which the soloist was David Grimal, the founder of the orchestra, and one month, when the cellist Xavier Phillips was in the foreground, the works composed by Enescu were not missing.
Both performances, held on the stage of Athens, showed the audience a different way of performing classical music.
Les Dissonances appeared on the music scene in 2004 as the only classical musical ensemble in which there was no conductor.
The conductor is the most important musician for musicians.
It is true, on the one hand, musicians need an education either to become soloists or to become performers in an orchestra – they speak of instrumentalists, not composers.
They are trained as “specialist workers.”
They feel like they need a conductor.
On the other side of the stage, for the public, the whole musical fetish is focused on the conductor.
And so, the business, the music industry, does its own marketing.
We are no longer talking about music.
So if we look at this world, we have skilled workers on the one hand, which is stupid, and an audience that can’t listen but has to look, which is stupid again,” Grimal said.
The violinist says that this change in the way he makes music came as a result of the "musical deceptions" of his solo career.
I was like a high-level athlete who had to do the same exercise around the world with different orchestras, to earn a lot of money and to bring money to the music industry.
Ten years ago, when I was about 30 years old, I found this very depressing, because I no longer found human creativity and brotherhood in this system.
So, I've found no point in continuing on this road.
So I decided to create Dissonances.
This happened in 2004, and at the time no one did this without a conductor: "The music world, extremely conservative, did not want such projects."
"How do you imagine marketing with a collective of musicians in which there is no ego?" asks the artist.
David Grimal acknowledges that Les Dissonaces is "a luxury", noting that none of the musicians who are part of the orchestra depend on the success of this project to live.
In 10 years of the ensemble's existence, the lack of a conductor has not proved to be an obstacle in the musical act: "Curiously, the more we sing a more complex repertoire, the simpler it seems, because all musicians are obliged to be present in the opera and not only in the role", says Grimal, adding that at the show on Sunday "we were 74 on the scene".
In Grimal’s opinion, the Enescu Festival is a “very courageous one”, precisely because he also invited Les Dissonances: “An extraordinary festival, where the greatest orchestras in the world are present who sing three times a day, and in the middle of these orchestras you have invited this strange group as well”.
In a temple of orchestral tradition, such as the Enescu Festival, there was a place and interest in something different that broke barriers.
