At the most anticipated meeting in recent years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it’s time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the meeting room of the central bank, will be seen a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed president, and her colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The central bank has been given a double task by Congress: to maximize the U.S. employment rate and maintain price stability.
But since the big economic crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the factor X in a decision that will be too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the US economy is ready to be relieved of the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in place from the end of 2008.
Even if most data point to a strong growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already wary of adding volatility by raising the benchmark rate to federal funds – even by only a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and the main issues that will follow,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were to look for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the world market would be enough to give them reason to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed’s decision, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of economists surveyed recently by Bloomberg have forecast an interest rate increase this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a drop on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers would mitigate the blow by promising it would take a long time until the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The move was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising for the Fed to raise the interest rate at this point,” Lonski said.
If Fed decision makers do this, “they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets.”
Other experts said an increase in the interest rate would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percent this month, the first small step toward a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected interest rates to rise this year despite objections from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Salary gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply falling oil prices.
“The economy can cope at higher rates and needs them, given the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to enter fibrillation at the end of this month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below the record high in May as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market declined somewhat this month, with the Dow index now about 10 percent below its May high.
For Fed decision makers, the market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the timing of the interest rate increase.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and news about the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, we would be more steadfast at the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now, he predicts that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they almost don’t have data to rely on after the events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
The mere allusion of then-president Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “enhance” its monetary expansion has triggered tremors in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected to not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
Its decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at well-being management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that “Fed has an oversized reaction history to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to economic bases.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported raising the interest rate, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that affected Asia caused the Fed to lower the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the implications of limited identification for US development,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials revisited the declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis such as the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate-setting commission.
The last turbulent period did not rise to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to get into the situation of fearing an interest rate increase because markets have been upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take premature action.
