Weight Reduction Surgery Could Be Useful For Diabetics With Mild Obesity
The benefits of weight reduction surgery for people with mild obesity and type 2 diabetes could last for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those who undergo non-surgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of measurement of weight relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18.5-24.9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy in the sleeve - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments for diabetes remained almost at the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes cured completely at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes cured completely in only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored the blood level of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects the level of blood sugar over time.
The researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the average haemoglobin A1c level decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at about 8%.
But this improved “glycaemic control” – reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels – did not reduce the death rate to five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the gastrectomy group in the sleeve, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), experienced more pronounced decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%) and had a higher likelihood of complete diabetes, 16% of complete diabetes remission.
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on heavyweights in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, School of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared with a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic aspect for people with BMI under 35 interested in the procedure.
“This is the point where this work is critical, because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that their patients and doctors should start taking their weight seriously when the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long to urge people to take this seriously,” she said.
I think once they’ve accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies, predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it’s extremely hard to get back to normal.
