Fourfold increase in the number of children who have ingested hand detergent in the past 4 years
According to the Georgia Anti-Poison Center, the U.S. Anti-Poison Centers have reported an increase of about 400% since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who have swallowed high-alcohol hand detergent.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Anti-Poison Center, cases of hand detergent ingestion in children under 12 years of age reported at anti-poison centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children have more frequent access to these products and unfortunately a percentage of them arrive at the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said some children intentionally drink detergent and others do it to impress their friends or respond to challenges on social media.
You can watch movies on YouTube that show teenagers how to drink detergent to create cheap drinks.
It turns out that teenagers have mixed the detergent with oral water with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the attractive smell of the detergent.
“A child doesn’t think it’s hurting them,” says Lopez.
Many of the most attractive types of hand detergents are perfumed.
Hand detergents with strawberry flavor, grapes, orange are the most attractive for children.
Hand detergent contains about 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few swallows can cause alcohol poisoning.
“It’s very concentrated alcohol,” Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison center at Kansas University Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave the same hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones get to them, this is a quick way to drink a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four strawberry-flavoured hand detergent sprays at school, has arrived at the emergency room for treatment.
She had blood alcohol179, twice the threshold at which an adult is considered by law under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah stinked and could not go when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage as the girl fell and hit her head because of alcohol, Ritchey said.
“It was frightening,” Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah’s mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free wet products or napkins and not to leave hand detergent out of the reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand detergent containing an undeclared toxic ingredient.
Sanitary authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, specified as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in northern New York plotted to poison their “bad” teacher by “putting antibacterial products in the classroom,” according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand detergent and banned it in her classroom.
The police considered the plan “insignificant” and referred the disciplinary matter to the school inspectorate.
