On Wednesday, the government approved the “National Strategy on Immigration for 2015-2018” and the “Action Plan for the current year”, documents considered to be “another stage that Romania is going through as part of efforts to modernize the process of managing immigration in the national territory”, according to a press release.
The strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action that reflect policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
Considering the problems faced by the countries in Romania’s immediate vicinity, measures are being considered for the uniform and coherent management of the situations caused by the possible influx of illegal immigrants into Romania, generated by crisis situations of a political, social, economic or military nature.
“The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay particular attention to citizens coming from states with potential migration or that can undermine national security,” the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reviving the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets several general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the residence of citizens of third countries on the territory of Romania and the appropriate application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the overall strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the territory of Romania for third-party citizens who meet the needs of employment, facilitating access for citizens of third countries to higher education institutions in Romania for the areas and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government considers that it is "a means of establishing concrete activities that will lead to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing phenomenon of migration".
