Zuckerberg said he wants to avoid the moments when someone posts on his account or a major event in his life, and someone else will “dislike” it.
Users of the network, which has reached 1.5 billion active accounts, have long asked to have the opportunity to express their negative emotions or empathize with something sad.
Zuckerberg said it was not comfortable for people to “like” current events, such as the refugee crisis, or the death of a family member.
“You may not feel comfortable giving that post a Like,” the Facebook representative said.
The new Facebook button hasn’t been well received by everyone.
"There's already enough hate on Facebook and social media," Haneef said on the New York Times' Facebook page.
"I'm going to dislike the dislike button," he said.
Roger Anderson, a microbiologist in Atlanta, said there was nothing wrong with the button, encouraging people to have different opinions on Facebook.
Debra Aho Williamson, a social media analyst at eMarketer, said it’s hard to imagine that a single button can convey a complex range of negative emotions.
Moreover, she argues, the election campaign is approaching in America, and the “Dislike” button would create a total disaster.
