There are many resentments, which are increasing in intensity even these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, which I had just recently sampled in Jean Clude Junker’s speech, is increasingly tending to make major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of member states in consultation with only a few European powers, mainly Germany.
And this is happening as electoral support for anti-immigration, anti-immigration and Eurosceptic groups increases dramatically across the continent.
In other words, the negatively charged emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever in the past.
This is what the Financial Times is doing when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation that starts from the international interest.
If voters make the brain decision, then the UK will remain in the EU.
