However, Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we are witnessing a more pronounced integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the countries in the region to the periphery of interest and decision-making in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States fuels his populist rhetoric from the frustrations accumulated in Western societies.
Because of economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed over the past decades, the generous social benefits, can no longer continue the same in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Euro-immigration zone, both provoked by hasty decisions that have taken into account only the integrationist political ambitions, not the ability and readiness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turmoil on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and can greatly affect Romania’s situation.
And it's hard to rule out anything from the standpoint of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to cope with such complicated situations.
